# .security-audit-allowlist
#
# Two formats supported (BTS-152):
#
#   1. Legacy file-only:
#        <file-substring>
#      Silences ALL findings whose file path contains the substring.
#      Coarse — current and future findings of any category are masked.
#
#   2. Per-finding triple (preferred for surgical scoping):
#        <file-substring>::<category>::<detail-substring>
#      Silences only findings matching ALL three: file substring AND
#      category exact AND detail substring. Empty <category> or
#      <detail-substring> acts as a wildcard for that segment. Empty
#      <file-substring> is rejected.
#      Recognized categories: secret, pii, email, dangerous-file.
#      Unknown categories are harmless (just won't match any finding).
#
# Lines starting with # and blank lines are ignored. Whitespace is trimmed.
# Malformed triples (fewer than 3 ::-separated segments) cause a load-time
# error.
#
# Each entry MUST include a comment explaining why the finding is
# allowlisted and what review surface still covers it.

# settings.json contains absolute path patterns (e.g., Read(//Users/...))
# that flag as PII because of the username segment. Permissions in this
# file are independently reviewed via permissions-audit.sh; the security
# audit's PII scan is redundant for permission entries by design.
# Origin: BTS-142 autonomy-first permissions rewrite. Tightened to a
# per-finding pattern in BTS-152 — secret/email/dangerous-file findings
# in the same file would now still surface.
.claude/settings.json::pii::Read(//Users/
